Several reasons - first, you don't want the underhood bits getting wet.
Yes, I know you had a car that was &quot;designed not to let rain water
come in&quot; but it eventually will.  Secondly, you have to have pretty good
control over the underhood fluids to keep Bad Things from happening to
your windshield (the latter learned the hard way while stuck in traffic
in a '53 Studebaker with a louvered hood and no &quot;catch can&quot;)

If underhood heat is a real concern - and it does not appear to be in
most cases - fender vents would be much more practical.

nate

